It is said that the Ameria apple is the best keeper and the honey—apple the worst. It is recommended that quinces should be stored in a place kept shut up, from which all draughts are excluded, or else that they should be boiled or soaked in honey. Pomegranates should be hardened in boiling sea-water and then dried in the sun for three days and hung up in such a way as to be pro- tected from the dew at night, and when wanted for use they should be thoroughly washed in fresh water.
